ieve in nature what laboratory researchers can only do with simplified experiments. Using historical frontiers as models, Kohler shows how biologists created vigorous new border sciences of ecology and evolutionary biology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBiologyxFieldwork. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  anaturalists, methodology, research, scholarship, quantitative science, scientific values, laboratory, field biologists, experiments, ecology, evolutionary biology, records, nature, data, environment, measurements, counting, quantifiable, place, biometry, genetics, vivaria, biological farms, marine stations, hybrid integration, speciation, species, geography, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022645009440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226450117423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226450117/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles